post_text:
You may have noticed that student schedules are available in PowerSchool. Unfortunately, we have encountered issues with the process that makes the schedules available to students and parents, and many student schedules are showing up incorrectly. We are aware of this problem, and are working to resolve it as soon as possible. We will send out another phone message and post on Facebook when schedules have been corrected. At that time, information will also be provided about how to request schedule changes. School counselors have reached out by email to many students who either did not turn in their course requests or who have scheduling conflicts, so please have your students check their school email account for messages from Mrs. Sutton or Mrs. Moore-Bowers.

If you have chosen e-learning for your students, their schedules will not immediately show this. Counselors will begin working on this process when they return to school next week.

Thank you for your patience while we work to make schedules available!

Hello Prairie Heights staff and community members. My name is Madison Strater. I am on the Yearbook staff for the high school.
We have been working tirelessly on bringing you a yearbook that we are proud of, but we need your help.

Because of COVID-19 and at-home learning, we desperately need photos to help populate our pages that would previously held Spring activities and end-of-the-year events and activities.

Here‚Äôs how you can help:
If you have photos from...
-2019 Spring Sports
-2019 Spring Activities/Events(Prom, Last Day of School, etc.)
-This Year‚Äôs General Student Life (Student Section, Random Photos of You and Friends, etc.)
-Senior Candids (Anything of Seniors Together)
-This Year‚Äôs Staff Photos
-2020 Photos of What You Did At Home During Quarantine

If you have any of the photos listed, please private message me them.

Any photo that you think would help and I didn‚Äôt mention it is greatly appreciated. Anything is welcome as long as it is appropriate!
Thank you!

We are ready to begin our 2020-2021 school year!

Registration will open July 20. We strongly encourage all families to find our registration link on our website beginning July 20 and register from home.

If you are not able to complete the online registration from home, please find a link to make an appointment beginning July 20. You may also call Nicole Whitsel, starting July 20, at 260-351-2523 to make an appointment. If you need an appointment to come to school to register, you will be limited to one person per family and you must wear a mask. *One appointment is needed to register all of the students in your family (regardless of their grade).

All parents/guardians of a PHCSC student will register at the middle school. You will enter door M1 at the front of the middle school. Appointments can be made July 22 or July 23 from 11AM-7PM.

More than 100 great students dreaming of coming to the US in August are still waiting for the amazing news that they have a host family. Kids like Diego from Spain, Ricardo from Brazil, Lilith from Germany, and Martina from Italy are looking forward to this school year with optimism and excitement. Can YOU help make their dreams come true? Do YOU have room in your heart for a new son or daughter, who will be in your home for a few short months, but a part of your family forever?

This year, more than ever, we need host families. In this time of uncertainty, we need families that believe we will come out the other side of this pandemic. Families that are willing to help build friendships and relationships that span the globe. üåç

Contact Sherri Parker, 574-453-0535 or sherri.jaynes.parker@gmail.com today for more information. No obligation, no high pressure, let's just talk about how easy it is to make a real difference in the world, one student at a time.

Please SHARE this post to help spread the word that host families just like YOU are needed!

Kids like Diego from Spain, Ricardo from Brazil, Lilith from Germany, and Martina from Italy are looking forward to this school year with optimism and excitement. Can YOU help make their dreams come true? Do YOU have room in your heart for a new son or daughter, who will be in your home for a few short months, but a part of your family forever?

This year, more than ever, we need host families. In this time of uncertainty, we need families that believe we will come out the other side of this pandemic. Families that are willing to help build friendships and relationships that span the globe. üåç

Contact Sherri Parker, 574-453-0535 or sherri.jaynes.parker@gmail.com today for more information. No obligation, no high pressure, let's just talk about how easy it is to make a real difference in the world, one student at a time.

Please SHARE this post to help spread the word that host families just like YOU are needed!

post_text:
Semester 2 Grade Information:

Prairie Heights High School has made the decision to modify the grade formula for this semester. Instead of our typical 45% weight for each quarter, there will not be separate grades for quarters 3 and 4, which will result in a single semester two grade. In other words, all of the grades from January 6th through the end of the school year will combine together and calculate into a semester two grade. We will be making decisions regarding final exams and what percentage they will be of the final grades for the semester at a later date.

Semester 2 Grade Information:

Prairie Heights High School has made the decision to modify the grade formula for this semester. Instead of our typical 45% weight for each quarter, there will not be separate grades for quarters 3 and 4, which will result in a single semester two grade. In other words, all of the grades from January 6th through the end of the school year will combine together and calculate into a semester two grade. We will be making decisions regarding final exams and what percentage they will be of the final grades for the semester at a later date.

post_text: The Class of 2020‚Äôs graduation commencement ceremony has been set for Friday, May 29th at 7:00 p.m. with Baccalaureate services being held prior to the ceremony at 5:45 p.m. In regards to our current situation with the temporary shut- down of school, we will be using the waiver days granted by Governor Holcomb to cover these missed days. With the uncertainty of any other mandates or guidelines that could be handed down from the state or national level in the future, please understand that this date could be postponed. However, if everything remains status quo, our goal is to utilize the waiver so that our 2020 graduates can walk across the stage on Friday, May 29th.

Attention Parents of Sophomore Students:

Beginning Tuesday, March 3, and throughout the next few weeks all sophomores will be taking the ISTEP+ exams in English and math. These tests are mandated by the state and are required for graduation.

Tuesday, March 3rd, Thursday, March 5th, and Tuesday, March 10th all sophomores will be taking the first round of the English ISTEP+ test.

Then on Thursday, March 12th and Tuesday, March 17th all sophomores will be taking the first round of the math ISTEP+ test.

Please encourage your students to get plenty of sleep, eat a good breakfast and lunch, dress comfortably, and, of course, BE HERE for the tests.

Please contact the school if you have any questions.

Congratulations to Corrine Reed and the PHHS Thespians for the following accolades at the Indiana State Thespian Conference held January 24-26:

-The PHHS International Thespians were awarded their 4th straight Gold Honor Troupe Award!

-The tech teams of Trey Best, Holden Frazier, Gabe Reed, Carver Teller, Grant Teller, Jodi Scofield, and Madelyn Wylie won 13 of the 19 tech categories

-The tech team of Holden Frazier, Gabe Reed, Carver Teller, and Grant Teller were also recognized as the top tech team in the state! All seven of these students will be moving on to Nationals in June at Bloomington, Indiana!

-The following students participated in the International Thespian Excellence Awards at the Indiana State Thespian Conference and all earned an Excellent ranking in their events: Mallori McGraw, David Claudy, and Travis Elliott in Monologues; Kiana Allshouse & Gabe Reed in Duet Acting, and Carver Teller, Trey Best, Travis Elliott, and Samuel Updike in Group Acting.

Congratulations to Blake Kain, Andrew Gunthorp, Leyton Keipper, and Sabrina Hinkle who competed in the state FFA welding contest. In the Beginner division, Sabrina individually placed 72 and Leyton was 54th out of 110 students. Together, their scores placed them 25th out of 60 teams. In the advanced division, individually, Blake was 4th and Andrew was 25th out of 119 students. Their combined scores placed them 4th out of 65 teams in the advanced division.
All together, with the 4 individual scores added together, PH was 7th out of 75 teams/schools that competed on Saturday.

Starting Monday, December 2nd and running through Thursday, December 5th we will be collecting food for our annual Christmas Drive. Donated items that would be appreciated to help our local families in need include: boxed foods, canned fruits vegetables and meats; paper products such as paper towels, napkins, and toilet paper; and personal care items such as toothpaste, soap, and shampoo.

This drive will be a class competition with the class bringing in the most items will receive pizza for lunch the following week.

If you would like to support a specific class we will also be collecting items at the following athletic events:
Wrestling November 26th
Boy‚Äôs Basketball November 27th
Girl‚Äôs Basketball November 29th and December 3rd
